<|startoftext|>Headline:Trump calls North Korean deal deal the worst ever: ABC News
Content: "NEW YORK (Reuters) - Trump called Friday s agreement by North Korean leader Kim Jong Un to shut down an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) test site in North Korea's northwest region the largest arms deal in history, ABC News reported on Sunday.  This deal provides arms that North Korea can use to shoot down a big target with nuclear weapons,  Trump told a live question-and-answer session with reporters aboard Air Force One as he arrived for a two-nation summit with Japan s Prime Minister Shinzo Abe.  This will be probably the most weapons deal in history, if not the biggest and most expensive weapons deal in history,  Trump said. Abe left New York on Monday to attend a summit with Abe s Japanese ally Prime Minister Shinzo Abe and Trump s U.S. ally Japan s Pacific ally Shinzo Abe.  Japan s Prime Minister Shinzo Abe joined Trump s Japanese counterpart Shinzo Abe for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in Panama s seaside resort of Mar del Plata, where bilateral and multilateral deals were discussed.   The two leaders also agreed on North Korean state sponsorship of terrorism, trade, and the fight against Islamic State militants, but there was no agreement on their common stance on North Korea, or any joint U.N.-China talks,  ABC News said, adding that Trump and Abe had remained more focused on getting North Korea off the brink of international sanctions than developing the missile and nuclear tests in which the regime is believed to have amassed two or more nuclear-tipped ICBMs. Trump, who took office on Jan. 20, took aim at North Korea s leader Kim Jong Un as he met with Abe and North Korean leader Trump on Sunday, tweeting  North Korea should focus on working to stop the nuclear program because only getting MAD will make it a disaster for the United States! North Korea is fast ratcheting up its weapons programs, including missile builds and nuclear tests. Kim, who has been living under U.N. sanctions since 2006, said in a statement on Friday Pyongyang would test a new intercontinental ballistic missile on Saturday, state media reported. A third missile test on Tuesday demonstrated the military capabilities of the regime, the statement said, state news agency KCNA showed. However, any test would be long overdue, as North Korea s nuclear and missile programmes are intermingled with other missile programs, including testing a powerful missile this year, a nuclear test in March, one U.S. official told Reuters last month. Trump will head to Asia on Thursday for the Group of 18 summits, the latest in Asia, to be attended by U.S., Japanese and North Korean leaders at the weekend. Abe and Abe have also agreed to increase North Korea s foreign aid to Japan to $1 billion this year and $5 billion over four years, a source at the meeting who had been briefed by Abe s office added. On Friday, Kim s son, Kim Konya, said the missile tests would  further confirm our resolve, with the aim of totally annihilating that enemy nation.  The agreement by the two countries means the United States will have a $2.5 billion fund providing loans and investment to North Korea s banking, construction and industrial sectors, according to the pact. ",<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Headline:"Putin, Trump to sign joint statement on Syria on Tuesday: TASS"
Content: "MOSCOW (Reuters) - Russian President Vladimir Putin and U.S. President Donald Trump, who attended a summit on Wednesday, will sign a joint statement on Monday concerning the Syrian civil war, TASS news agency reported on Sunday.  The statement will be signed by Putin and Trump, and consists of a group of seven members,  TASS cited a Kremlin aide as telling reporters.  Syria crisis is the subject of many discussions, and today the president and Putin are scheduled to speak by phone about Syria,  he said. ",<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Headline:Britain's May has no regrets over Brexit deal
